	{
		"title": "Quivering Statue",
		"level": 5,
		"school": "Alteration",
		"type": "Elemental",
		"Casting Time": "7; see below",
			"Range": "Touch",
			"AOE": "Caster or one recipient",
			"Duration": "1 hour / caster level",
			"Save": "See below",
			"Description": "<p>When <em class=\"spellname\">Quivering Statue</em> is cast the wizard, or other willing creature, turns to solid stone, along with any garments and equipment. The initial transformation from flesh to stone requires one full round after the spell is cast.</p><p>During the transformation, there is an <strong>20% -Con</strong> chance that the recipient dies from shock. If this occurs, the result is usually an ugly twisted amalgam of flesh and stone.</p><p>If the spell is successful, the creature can withstand any mundane inspection and appear to be a stone statue. <em class=\"spell\">Detect Arcane Magic</em> will discover a faint aura, however. Despite being in this condition, the petrified individual can see, hear, and smell normally. Their sense of feeling is mostly gone; only major impacts can be detected.</p><p>The individual affected by <em class=\"spellname\">Quivering Statue</em> can return to his normal state instantly, act, and then return to the <em class=\"spellname\">Statue</em> state, all within the same Initiative Count. This shift usually applies a -3 to the <em>Surprise</em> rolls of enemies. If an attacker can act simultaneously, they can injure his fleshly form. These later changes of form do not require a system shock roll to survive.</p><p>While a <em class=\"spellname\">Statue</em>, the recipient is vulnerable only to harm that can damage solid stone. Heavy impacts from blunt objects or long falls onto a hard surface may injure them.</p><p>If a <em class=\"spell\">Transmute Rock To Mud</em>, <em class=\"spell\">Sculptor's Hands</em>, or <em class=\"spell priest\">Shape Stone</em> spell is successfully cast upon the recipient, they will usually perish.</p><p><em class=\"spell\">Curse Of The Medusae (reversed)</em> or <em class=\"spell\">Dispel Arcane Magic</em> can be used to end the <em class=\"spellname\">Quivering Statue</em> effect.</p>"
	},
	{
		"title": "Radiant Stave Of Woe",
		"level": 7,
		"school": "Conjuration, Evocation",
		"type": "Demonic",
		"Casting Time": "10",
			"Range": "Touch",
			"AOE": "One staff",
			"Duration": "1 round / caster level",
			"Save": "See below",
			"Description": "<p>This spell requires the caster to hold a mundane staff as he casts it. Upon completion it begins to crawl with black light, and to give off an unsettling insectile buzz.</p><p>A <em class=\"spellname\">Radiant Stave Of Woe</em> is a +4 weapon that inflicts 2d6+1 HP damage on a strike, with several other effects. Only the caster can safely touch it; all others are affected as follows:</p><ul><li>One point of damage done is permanently lost, unless a Save is made. A <em class=\"spell priest\">Heal</em> or similar magic will restore the injury.</li><li>Its touch acts as a <em class=\"spell\">Dispel Arcane Magic</em> of half the caster's level.</li><li>Any caster hit loses 1 memorised spell at random; creatures with spell-like abilities lose the use of one for 5 rounds. In both cases a Save negates the effect.</li><li>Finally, injury to the victim's mind may occur (roll d100):<dl class=\"diceroll\"><dt>01-45</dt><dd>No effect</dd><dt>46-65</dt><dd><em class=\"spell\">Sow Confusion</em> for 1d4 rounds</dd><dt>66-75</dt><dd><em>Stun</em>, as <em class=\"spell\">Great Sigil</em> for 1d6 rounds</dd><dt>76-85</dt><dd><em class=\"spell\">Know Fear</em> for 2d4 rounds</dd><dt>86-95</dt><dd><em>Despair</em>, as <em class=\"spell\">Instil Emotion</em> for 1d6 rounds</dd><dt>96-00</dt><dd><em class=\"spell\">Elruss' Enfeeblement Of The Cognate Mind</em> for 1d6 rounds</dd></dl><p>None of the above effects allow a Save.</p></li></ul><p>A <em class=\"spellname\">Radiant Stave Of Woe</em> is immune to all magical attacks and effects except <em class=\"spell\">Mordenkainen's Disjunction</em> and <em class=\"spell\">Wish</em>. Once the duration is up, the staff burns away and is destroyed.</p><p>The ancient wizard and expert on the Infernal, <em>Nezram</em>, called <em>the Demon-Ridden</em>, once stated that a <em class=\"spellname\">Radiant Stave</em> is the temporary residence of a demon, and refused to make use of the spell.</p>"
	},
