		"Duration": "Permanent; see below",
		"Save": "See below",
		"Description": "<p>This spell can be used to permanently secure an area against intrusion by non-believers. The area must already be consecrated to the caster's faith. If this consecration is disturbed, the <em class=\"spellname\">Forbiddance</em> falls too.</p><p>The effect on those entering the enchanted area is based on their faith (or alignment, for other-worldly or strongly-aligned beings), relative to the caster's:</p><dl class=\"detailed\"><dt>Same faith</dt><dd>No effect; can enter and leave the area at will. They will feel that the area is a friendly and welcoming place.</dd><dt>Allied faith</dt><dd>Save or be barred from the area.</dd><dt>Neutral faith or none</dt><dd>Save or be barred from the area; if failed, also suffer 2d6 HP damage. If they succeed, they can enter, but the area will make them tense and uneasy. While within, they have a penalty of -2 to Saves vs <em>fear</em> effects and <em>Concentration</em> rolls.</dd><dt>Enemy faith</dt><dd>Save or be barred from the area; if failed, also suffer 4d6 HP damage. If they succeed, they can enter, but the area is abhorrent to them. While within, they have a penalty of -4 to Saves vs <em>fear</em> effects and <em>Concentration</em> rolls.</dd></dl><p>Any creature who successfully enters the area, leaves and attempts to re-enter must undergo the same test.</p><p>A <em class=\"spellname\">Forbiddance</em> does not block missiles or spell casting across the barrier, but the spell does also prevent entry via <em class=\"spell\">Teleport</em> and similar magics, including Ethereal intrusion.</p><p>The area within a <em class=\"spellname\">Forbiddance</em> can be further protected by either a <em class=\"spell priest\">Sanctify</em> or an <em class=\"spell priest\">Exaltation</em>.</p>"
